#X text 33 85 The [mtof] object converts a MIDI pitch value to a frequency
in Hertz (so that "69" converts to "440"). Microtonal pitches are possible
\, where "69.5" is a quarter tone higher than 69 (or 50 cents higher
\, so 0.01 = 1 cent)., f 69;
#X text 33 147 The [ftom] object does the reverse. A frequency of zero
Hertz is given a MIDI value of -1500 (strictly speaking \, it's negative
infinity.), f 69;
#X text 33 364 A dBFS scale is possible if you simply add 100 to the
dB input value or subtract 100 from the dB output value (in this case
\, minus infinity dB is clipped to -100 dBFS)., f 69;
#X text 33 417 Finally \, [dbtopow] and [powtodb] convert decibels
to and from power units \, equal to the square of the "RMS" amplitude.
, f 69;
#X text 33 301 The [rmstodb] object does the opposite conversion and
Zero "RMS" amplitude (strictly speaking \, minus infinity dB) is clipped
to zero dB. Note that "RMS" may be a bit misleading as you can also
consider that the linear amplitude value refers to "peak" amplitude
as well., f 69;
#X text 33 196 The [dbtorms] object converts from dB to linear ("RMS")
amplitude. Decibels in Pd are basically dBFS with an offset of 100!
Hence \, the typical range is arbitrarily set from 0 to 100 dB (where
100 dB corresponds to an "RMS" of 1). When converted to linear amplitude
\, negative dB values are clipped to zero "RMS" and zero dB \, which
should correspond to 1e-05 in linear "RMS" \, is rounded down to zero
instead., f 69;
